17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 10 O.S. 2021, Section 601.6, as
19 amended by Section 1, Chapter 178, O.S.L. 2025 (10 O.S. Supp. 2025,
20 Section 601.6), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 601.6. A. For purposes of this section, the term
22 "children and youth service system" shall have the same meaning as
23 it is defined in Section 600 of this title.
24
Req. No. 17156 Page 1

1 B. The Office of Juvenile System Oversight shall have the
2 responsibility of inspecting and investigating misfeasance and
3 malfeasance within the children and youth service system, as
4 directed by the Oklahoma Commission on Children and Youth, to
5 ascertain compliance with established responsibilities.
6 C. The Office shall conduct not less than one but not more than
7 two regular, periodic, unannounced inspections of state-operated
8 children's institutions and facilities annually. The Office is
9 further authorized to inspect privately operated children's
10 institutions and facilities that receive state or federal funding,
11 on a periodic basis or as needed.
12 D. The Office shall investigate complaints filed with the
13 Office regarding the children and youth service system.
14 E. The Office of Juvenile System Oversight shall have the
15 authority to:
16 1. Access all facilities within the children and youth service
17 system for the purpose of conducting inspections and investigations;
18 2. Examine and copy all records and budgets pertaining to the
19 children and youth service system and to review inspection reports
20 of the State Fire Marshal, State Department of Health, and any other
21 agency that accredits such institutions and facilities;
22 3. Interview the residents of institutions and facilities
23 within the children and youth service system;
24 4. Subpoena witnesses and hold public hearings;
Req. No. 17156 Page 2

1 5. Establish, in accordance with the Dispute Resolution Act,
2 Sections 1801 through 1813 of Title 12 of the Oklahoma Statutes, a
3 voluntary program for foster parents to mediate complaints
4 concerning the rights of foster parents, as provided for in Section
5 1-9-119 of Title 10A of the Oklahoma Statutes, that relate to
6 certain actions, inactions or decisions of the Department of Human
7 Services, the Department of Juvenile Justice, or child-placing
8 agencies that may adversely affect the safety and well-being of
9 children in the custody of the state;
10 6. Receive any complaint alleging that an employee of the
11 Department of Human Services or a child-placing agency has
12 threatened a foster parent with removal of a child from the foster
13 parent, harassed a foster parent, or refused to place a child in a
14 licensed or certified foster home, or disrupted a child placement as
15 retaliation or discrimination towards a foster parent who has:
16 a. filed a grievance pursuant to Section 1-9-120 of Title
17 10A of the Oklahoma Statutes,
18 b. provided information to any state official or
19 Department employee, or
20 c. testified, assisted, or otherwise participated in an
21 investigation, proceeding, or hearing against the
22 Department or child-placing agency.
23 The Office of Juvenile System Oversight shall forward the
24 complaints to the Office of Client Advocacy for investigation
Req. No. 17156 Page 3

1 purs uant to subsection D of Section 1-9-112 of Title 10A of the
2 Oklahoma Statutes. The Office of Juvenile System Oversight shall
3 work with the Office of Client Advocacy to ensure the complaints are
4 investigated and resolved in accordance with the grievance
5 procedures provided in Section 1-9-120 of Title 10A of the Oklahoma
6 Statutes. The provisions of this paragraph shall not apply to any
7 complaint by a foster parent regarding the result of a criminal,
8 administrative, or civil proceeding for a violation of any law,
9 rule, or contract provision by that foster parent, or the action
10 taken by the Department or a child-placing agency in conformity with
11 the result of any such proceeding;
12 7. Issue reports to the Governor, Speaker of the House of
13 Representatives, President Pro Tempore of the Senate, Chief Justice
14 of the Supreme Court of the State of Oklahoma, any appropriate
15 prosecutorial agency, the director of the agency under
16 consideration, and other persons as necessary and appropriate; and
17 8. Provide recommendations to the Oklahoma Commission on
18 Children and Youth on or before May 1 of each year.
19 F. The Office of Juvenile System Oversight shall not release
20 information that would identify a person who makes a complaint to
21 the Office, unless a:
22 1. A court of competent jurisdiction orders release of the
23 information for good cause shown; or
24
Req. No. 17156 Page 4

1 2. The disclosure of such information is made to an appropriate
2 law enforcement agency when necessary to protect the safety of
3 others after a complainant communicates an imminent and credible
4 threat against an individual or entity that a reasonable person
5 would interpret as a serious expression of intent to commit an act
6 of unlawful violence. Such information shall not be disclosed to
7 any other person or entity except pursuant to an order of a court of
8 competent jurisdiction.
9 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
